Fetch Race Condition

In this challenge, you'll attempt to solve a real-world bug I ran into.

I describe the problem in this brief intro video:

Difficulty

This is a very hard problem. Unless you have extensive React experience, you probably won't be able to solve it.

Rules

  • Feel free to google anything you'd like.
  • You're not allowed to install any additional third-party dependencies.

Playground

Code Playground

import React from 'react';

const ENDPOINT =
'https://jor-test-api.vercel.app/api/get-price-for-quantity';

function App() {
const [quantity, setQuantity] = React.useState(1);
const [price, setPrice] = React.useState(null);
const id = React.useId();

React.useEffect(() => {
async function runEffect() {
const response = await fetch(
`${ENDPOINT}?quantity=${quantity}`
);
const data = await response.json();
setPrice(data.price);
}

runEffect();
}, [quantity]);

return (
<div className="wrapper">
<img
src="https://courses.joshwcomeau.com/images/joy-of-react-mascot.png"
alt=""
className="mascot"
/>
<form>
<div className="row">
<label htmlFor={id}>Quantity:</label>
<input
id={id}
type="number"
min={1}
max={50}
value={quantity}
onChange={(event) => {
setQuantity(event.target.value);
}}
/>
</div>

<button>
Buy {quantity} unit(s) for ${price}
</button>
</form>
</div>
);
}

export default App;

The first thing we need to understand is why this is happening.

With this setup, we need to fetch the price from the API, passing the quantity as a parameter. This is done because the backend is the "source of truth" for the price.

The trouble is that there's a bit of built-in randomness when it comes to network requests. The same request might take 500ms or 800ms or 1200ms. And so, we can wind up in situations where the final request to complete was actually a stale request.

This leads to situations like this:

The final result, in this situation, would be that quantity is set to 2, but price would only be $100, instead of $200.

To fix this problem, you'll need to figure out how to ignore the responses from stale requests.

There is a way to cancel Fetch requests, using the AbortController API. Personally, though, I find this API kinda clunky, not so much fun to work with.

Instead, I solved this problem by essentially generating a new ID for each fetch request, at the moment the request starts. I store this value in a ref.

Then, when the request finishes, I can check and see: is this request the most recently-generated one? If not, I can ignore the response, and not change any state.

One remaining quirk is that when the user changes the quantity, it continues to show the old, outdated price until that request is complete.

I created a state variable called status, so that I could track whether a request was ongoing or not. When the request starts, I set it to "loading". When it resolves, I set it to "idle".

While the status is "loading", I show a loading state. In a real app, I would include a spinner, but for now, we can add some text like "Calculating".

Why a ref? (info)

In the video above, I use a ref for fetchIndex, rather than a state variable. This is pretty weird, right?

I dig into it in this special bonus video:

In this video, I mention useEffectEvent. You can learn a bit more about this upcoming React API in the official docs.

Attempt code (success)
import React from 'react';


const ENDPOINT =
  'https://jor-test-api.vercel.app/api/get-price-for-quantity';


function App() {
  const [quantity, setQuantity] = React.useState(1);
  const [price, setPrice] = React.useState(null);
  // calculating || idle
  const [status, setStatus] =
    React.useState('calculating');


  const fetchIndex = React.useRef(0);


  const id = React.useId();


  React.useEffect(() => {
    async function runEffect() {
      setStatus('calculating');


      const startingFetchIndex = fetchIndex.current + 1;
      fetchIndex.current = startingFetchIndex;


      const response = await fetch(
        `${ENDPOINT}?quantity=${quantity}`
      );
      const data = await response.json();


      if (startingFetchIndex === fetchIndex.current) {
        setPrice(data.price);
        setStatus('idle');
      }
    }


    runEffect();
  }, [quantity]);


  return (
    <div className="wrapper">
      <img
        src="https://courses.joshwcomeau.com/images/joy-of-react-mascot.png"
        alt=""
        className="mascot"
      />
      <form>
        <div className="row">
          <label htmlFor={id}>Quantity:</label>
          <input
            id={id}
            type="number"
            min={1}
            max={50}
            value={quantity}
            onChange={(event) => {
              setQuantity(event.target.value);
            }}
          />
        </div>


        <button>
          {status === 'idle'
            ? `Buy ${quantity} unit(s) for $${price}`
            : 'Calculating…'}
        </button>
      </form>
    </div>
  );
}


export default App;
